We revisit the finite time singularity formation of Krieger-Schlag-Tataru [KST09] for the focusing energy critical wave equation in $\mathbb{R}^{3+1}$ from a geometric singular-analytic point of view, following Hintz [Hintz23]. We construct $C^{
u/2-}$ regular approximate solutions that settle down to multiple solitons, shrinking at a rate $t^{
u}$ with $
u>1$, and approaching the origin on different geodesics $\{x=zt\}$. By fine tuning the velocities, sizes and signs of the solitons, we are able to construct smooth ans"atze with any $
u>8$. Using robust energy estimates, the ans"atze are corrected to exact solutions.

Urban green spaces are increasingly recognized as actionable carbon sinks, yet their carbon stocks and greening potential remain poorly constrained in arid and rapidly urbanizing regions. We quantified campus-scale carbon storage and identified vegetation-driven opportunities for enhancing the urban carbon sink using an integrated remote sensing and ecosystem-service modelling workflow. The study was conducted at King Faisal University, Al-Ahsa, Saudi Arabia (≈100 ha; 25.334°N, 49.602°E). Sentinel-2 (10 m) and PlanetScope (3 m) imagery were used to derive NDVI-based land-cover areas, and YOLOv5 object detection provided a vegetation inventory. Carbon stocks were estimated with the InVEST Carbon Storage model parameterized by land-cover class. PlanetScope detected substantially more fragmented green space than Sentinel-2 (0.0890 vs. 0.0465 km
2
; +91.4%), indicating resolution-driven underestimation of small vegetation patches in moderate-resolution imagery. Estimated carbon density was highest in green land (62 t C ha
−1
) and lower in built-up (28 t C ha
−1
), bare land (21 t C ha
−1
), and other/paved surfaces (15 t C ha
−1
), yielding a total standing stock of 2,655.98 tonnes C. YOLOv5 identified 2,762 vegetation objects (1,273 trees; 1,489 plants/shrubs), supporting repeatable monitoring. A benchmark greening scenario (CD_potential = 62 t C ha
−1
) indicated an additional storage potential of 3,544.02 tonnes C if low-carbon land covers were enhanced toward high-biomass vegetated conditions. These estimates represent standing carbon stocks and scenario-based additional storage potential, rather than net carbon sequestration rates (which would require temporal monitoring and accounting for management-related emissions). This framework demonstrates how multi-resolution earth observation and AI-enabled vegetation inventorying can support carbon-focused campus planning by prioritizing protection of existing vegetation and targeted greening interventions.
